{{Infobox journal | title = Music Theory Spectrum | cover = [[File:Music Theory Spectrum.jpg]] | editor = Michael Cherlin | discipline = [[Music theory]] | peer-reviewed = | language = English | former_names = | abbreviation = Music Theory Spectr. | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | country = United States | frequency = Biannually | history = 1979-present | openaccess = | license = | impact = | impact-year = | website =https://mts.oxfordjournals.org/ | link1 = | link1-name = | link2 = | link2-name = | JSTOR = 01956167 | OCLC = 225222134 | LCCN = 79644237 | CODEN = | ISSN = 0195-6167 | eISSN = 1533-8339 | boxwidth = }}
'''''Music Theory Spectrum''''' ({{ISSN|0195-6167}}) is a peer-reviewed, [[academic journal]] specializing in [[music theory]] and [[musical analysis|analysis]]. It is the official journal of the [[Society for Music Theory]], and is published by [[Oxford University Press]]. The journal was first published in 1979 as the official organ of the Society for Music Theory, which had been founded in 1977 and had its first conference in 1978.<ref name="berry">{{citation|first=David Carson|last=Berry|authorlink=David Carson Berry|title=Schenkerian Theory in the United States: A Review of Its Establishment and a Survey of Current Research Topics|journal=Zeitschrift der Gesellschaft für Musiktheorie|volume=2|issue=2–3|year=2005|pages=111–112|url=http://www.gmth.de/zeitschrift/artikel/206.aspx}}.</ref> Unlike many other journals (music or otherwise), ''Music Theory Spectrum'' was initially published in an oblong (landscape) [[Page orientation|page format]], to better accommodate such musical graphics as [[Schenkerian analysis|Schenkerian]] graphs.<ref name="berry"/>
Published twice annually, ''Music Theory Spectrum'' includes research articles and book reviews. Online access to back issues of the journal is provided through [[JSTOR]].<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/journals/01956167.html JSTOR: Music Theory Spectrum].</ref> In a 1999 study, it was the seventh most frequently cited journal in music theses overall, and the third most frequently cited journal in music theory theses.<ref>{{citation|first=Lois|last=Kuyper-Rushing|title=Identifying Uniform Core Journal Titles for Music Libraries: A Dissertation Citation Study|year=1999|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/acrl/publications/crljournal/1999/mar/kuyper.pdf|journal=College & Research Libraries Journal|volume=60|issue=2|pages=153–163|doi=10.5860/crl.60.2.153}}.</ref>
In Spring 2014, [[Oxford University Press]] began publishing ''Music Theory Spectrum'', beginning with Volume 36, Issue 1. It replaced the [[University of California Press]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Theory Spectrum|url=https://societymusictheory.org/music-theory-spectrum|website=Society for Music Theory}}</ref>
''Music Theory Spectrum'' is currently edited by Michael Cherlin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music Theory Spectrum|url=http://mts.oxfordjournals.org/|website=Oxford Journals}}</ref> Its first editor was Bryan Simms, and other past editors have included Severine Neff, Joel Lester, Philip Lambert, [[Daniel Harrison (music theorist)|Daniel Harrison]], and [[Henry Klumpenhouwer]].
